<para id="fs-idp214119760">The electron volt (eV) is a convenient unit of energy for expressing atomic-scale energies. It is the amount of energy that an electron gains when subjected to a potential of 1 volt; 1 eV = 1.602 <m:math><m:mo>×</m:mo></m:math> 10<sup>–19</sup> J. Using the Bohr model, determine the energy, in electron volts, of the photon produced when an electron in a hydrogen atom moves from the orbit with <emphasis effect="italics">n</emphasis> = 5 to the orbit with <emphasis effect="italics">n</emphasis> = 2. Show your calculations.</para></problem>
